<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-12-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-12-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="338" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d338">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Bigelow</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 5.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-12-26"><hi rend="italic">December</hi> 26, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Mr. Pennington’s despatch of the 7th of
                            December, No. 2, has been received, and I have read with mingled
                            emotions of sorrow and pride the description it gives of the tributes so
                            worthily paid in Paris by the government of the Emperor and the foreign
                            legations, and the press of the metropolis, to the memory of William L.
                            Dayton, esq., our late minister to France.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM,H. SEWARD,</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">John Bigelow,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c</hi>.</p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>